Adjust rack to top position and heat broiler to high. Wash and dry produce.

Halve, core, and thinly slice @Long Green Pepper{1}(halved, cored, and thinly sliced) crosswise into strips.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @Sour Cream{3%tablespoon} with @Hot Sauce{1%teaspoon} to taste. Stir in water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{} in a #large ovenproof pan{} over medium-high heat. Add green pepper; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until softened and lightly blistered, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add another drizzle of oil and shrimp to pan with green pepper. Season with @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tablespoon}, salt, and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally (no need to break up into pieces!), until opaque and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> Rinse shrimp under cold water; pat dry with paper towels. Open package of chicken and drain off any excess liquid. Swap in shrimp or chicken for beef. Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

Stir in one-quarter of the @Green Salsa{7.06%ounce} (you'll use the rest in the next step); taste and season with salt and pepper.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #medium bowl{}. Wipe out pan.

Place a small amount of beef filling on one half of each @Flour Tortillas{6}. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create enchiladas. Place seam sides down in pan used to cook filling.

> TIP: For 4 servings or if pan isn't ovenproof, place enchiladas in a 9-by-13-inch baking dish.

Top with remaining salsa and sprinkle with @Mexican Cheese Blend{½%cup}.

Broil enchiladas until browned and bubbly, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> TIP: Watch carefully to avoid burning.

Drizzle with crema and serve.